DOC.TEXT:
   Skies were hazy over much of the country early today, with
morning temperatures already in the 70s and 80s _ and climbing _
after a night of thunderstorms, including one that beaned Minnesota
with baseball-sized hail.
   The forecast for the nation was hot _ one of the worst days in a
late-summer heat wave.
   High pressure stretching from coast to coast was expected to
bring temperatures in the 90s to the East, South and West and highs
in the 100s to the Plains and Southwest. Heat advisories were in
effect for Arkansas and Kentucky.
   The only cooler spots foreseen were in the Great Lakes and the
Pacific Northwest regions, where showers were likely with highs in
the 80s. Showers were also forming over Florida, Texas and
Louisiana and Arizona and New Mexico.
   On Monday, several cities in Texas, Kansas and Louisiana broke
or tied records for high temperatures. Those record were in danger
of being broken today.
   The high for the nation Monday was 106 degrees at Austin, Texas;
Medicine Lodge, Kan.; Waco, Texas, and Wichita, Kan.
   Other reports at 5 a.m. EDT:
